{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Conclusion\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The biblehub definition captures only the eschatological layer. The full diachronic picture is:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b Archaic root:} {\i kol\u225 ?z\u333 ?} means to cut short, check, restrain. {\i K\u243 ?lasis} is physical constraint and ordeal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b Classical/Hellenistic definition:} {\i k\u243 ?lasis} is corrective punishment, therapy for the soul, explicitly distinguished from retributive {\i tim\u333 ?r\u237 ?a}.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b Late-antique tension:} the philosophical tradition maintains the corrective sense (Damascius, Olympiodorus) while the biblical tradition introduces retributive eschatology.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A more accurate definition: corrective punishment or discipline, intended for the improvement of the one punished, rooted in the verb {\i kol\u225 ?z\u333 ?} meaning to cut short, check, or restrain; in biblical usage, also retributive or eternal punishment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Reference table\par}
